    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Multiple-word terms or names that are arranged in the form used in speech or written text. Examples are Christopher Wren and flying buttresses. Distinguished from inverted terms or names.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051198/Harpring, Introduction to Controlled Vocabularies (2010)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Termen of namen met meerdere woorden die gerangschikt zijn in de vorm die in het spraakgebruik of in geschreven tekst meestal wordt gehanteerd. Voorbeelden zijn 'Louis Couperus' en 'echte herten'. De term wordt gebruikt ter onderscheid van geïnverteerde termen of namen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
